]></dc:creator></item><item><title>?</title><link>https://imgur.com/gallery/yEFhqt3</link><description><![CDATA[<div><img alt="" src="https://i.imgur.com/HjIbw2S.jpg" style="max-width: 90%; height: auto;"></div><div><span></span></div></div>]]></description><guid>https://imgur.com/a/yEFhqt3</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[mfrybeasley]]></dc:creator></item><item><title>Why Maus Matters</title><link>https://imgur.com/gallery/avNEJIw</link><description><![CDATA[<div><img alt="" src="https://i.imgur.com/DQObXSE.jpg" style="max-width: 90%; height: auto;"></div><div><span></span></div><div>This Twitter thread reflects a lot of the conversation I've heard in the Jewish community lately about why books like Maus matter and why books like The Boy in the Striped Pajamas don't quite cut it. It's worth reading, but TL:DR: Boy in the Striped Pajamas is written to make people feel comfortable about the Holocaust being a General Sad Thing with neat lessons to learn about bigotry. It's a non Jewish perspective, with non of the sense of the Jewish world that was lost. Maus is a real story, with real implications.</div><div><img alt="" src="https://i.imgur.com/3bxE1nz.jpg" style="max-width: 90%; height: auto;"></div><div><span></span></div><div><img alt="" src="https://i.imgur.com/8o20UvE.jpg" style="max-width: 90%; height: auto;"></div><div><span></span></div><div><img alt="" src="https://i.imgur.com/X6Km9lW.jpg" style="max-width: 90%; height: auto;"></div><div><span></span></div><div>When my grandma was a child in 1930s Germany, other kids threw stones at her for beinga Jew when she tried to play outside.</div><div><img alt="" src="https://i.imgur.com/yrecr4K.jpg" style="max-width: 90%; height: auto;"></div><div><span></span></div><div><img alt="" src="https://i.imgur.com/pW9xAwp.jpg" style="max-width: 90%; height: auto;"></div><div><span></span></div><div><img alt="" src="https://i.imgur.com/QjpCVDS.jpg" style="max-width: 90%; height: auto;"></div><div><span></span></div><div><img alt="" src="https://i.imgur.com/lRTbjsM.jpg" style="max-width: 90%; height: auto;"></div><div><span></span></div><div><img alt="" src="https://i.imgur.com/HBZqMql.jpg" style="max-width: 90%; height: auto;"></div><div><span></span></div><div><img alt="" src="https://i.imgur.com/EoBWeei.jpg" style="max-width: 90%; height: auto;"></div><div><span></span></div><div>My grandma was a survivor and that intergenerational trauma thing is real.</div><div><img alt="" src="https://i.imgur.com/TIfa5J3.jpg" style="max-width: 90%; height: auto;"></div><div><span></span></div><div><img alt="" src="https://i.imgur.com/uRNkoyA.jpg" style="max-width: 90%; height: auto;"></div><div><span></span></div><div><img alt="" src="https://i.imgur.com/ISLb0nj.jpg" style="max-width: 90%; height: auto;"></div><div><span></span></div><div>Another post I saw described The Boy in the Striped Pajamas of being an example of Holocaust historical fiction that depicts "Good Gentiles Doing Good Things." Even though the Righteous among the nations (including those that saved my grandmother) were a stasticial anomaly, these stories focus on them, helping their non Jewish readership feel more comfortable and less reflective.</div></div>]]></description><guid>https://imgur.com/a/avNEJIw</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[AngryTeacher]]></dc:creator></item><item><title>Wholesome post to brighten your day 596</title><link>https://imgur.com/gallery/VslRxgo</link><description><![CDATA[<div><img alt="" src="https://i.imgur.com/6ZTcWsT.jpg" style="max-width: 90%; height: auto;"></div><div><span></span></div><div>https://imgur.com/gallery/5RkZEL6 Wholesome Post 595
